_km2           =\n|area_water_percent       =\n|area_urban_km2           =\n|area_metro_km2           =\n|area_blank1_title        =\n|area_blank1_km2          =\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_ft           =\n|elevation_max_m            =\n|elevation_max_ft           =\n|elevation_min_m            =\n|elevation_min_ft           =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               =2010\n|population_footnotes           =<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.luqyu.cn/tongjishow.asp?tid=983&aname=&yid=2010 |title=According to 2010 China National Census |access-date=2011-06-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406235036/http://www.luqyu.cn/tongjishow.asp?tid=983&aname=&yid=2010 |archive-date=2012-04-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =5586200\n|population_density_km2         =auto<!--For automatic calculation, any density field may contain: auto -->\n|population_metro               =\n|population_density_metro_km2   =\n|population_urban               =\n|population_density_urban_km2   =\n|population_blank1_title        =\n|population_blank1              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2  =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[China Standard Time|China Standard]]\n|utc_offset             = +08:00\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       = <!--  [[Postal code of China|Postal code]] -->\n|postal_code            = 253000\n|area_code              = 0534\n|iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-SD-14]]\n|blank_name             =[[GDP]]\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =GDP per capita\n|blank1_info            =\n|blank2_name            =[[Licence plates of the People's Republic of China|License Plate]] Prefix\n|blank2_info            = {{lang|zh-cn|\u9c81N}}\n|website                = {{URL|dz.gov.cn/}}\n|footnotes              =\n}} \n'''Dezhou''' ({{zh|c=\u5fb7\u5dde|p=D\u00e9zh\u014du}}) is a [[prefecture-level city]] in northwestern [[Shandong]] province, [[People's Republic of China]]. It borders the provincial capital of [[Jinan]] to the southeast, [[Liaocheng]] to the southwest, [[Binzhou]] to the northeast, and the province of [[Hebei]] to the north.\n\n==History==\n===Sulu Royal Family===\nThe King of [[Sulu]] [[Paduka Pahala]] from the [[List of sultans of Sulu#Pre-Sultanate Kings|first royal family on Sulu]] before the [[List of sultans of Sulu#Past Hashemite Sultans|Hashemites]] went on a tribute mission to the Ming dynasty [[Yongle Emperor]]. He died of natural causes in China and his two sons and wife were left in the care of [[Hui people|Hui Muslims]] in Dezhou, Shandong.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Steinhardt|first=Nancy Shatzman|title=China's Early Mosques|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4744-3721-9|location=Edinburgh|pages=161\u2013162}}</ref> The two families descended from the two sons were given the surnames An and Wen by the Ming Emperors. They lived through the Ming and Qing dynasties and still live in Dezhou today.{{by whom|date=October 2015}}{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nThe Kingdom of Sulu was converted to Islam, and the Hashemite [[Sharif ul-H\u0101shim of Sulu]] arrived in Sulu and married a princess of the previous non-Hashemite royal family, founding the [[Sulu Sultanate]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nTausug delegations from Sulu have visited Dezhou to see the descendants of the previous royal family.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n==Administration==\n{{see also|Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China}}\nThe [[prefecture-level city|municipality]] of Dezhou comprises thirteen [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|county-level sub divisions]]:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dezhou.gov.cn/zjdz/xsqjj/ |title=Political divisions of Dezhou City |access-date=2011-06-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723132710/http://www.dezhou.gov.cn/zjdz/xsqjj/ |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n;Districts\n*[[Decheng District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fb7\u57ce\u533a}}). The government of the prefecture-level city is located in this sub division.\n*[[Lingcheng District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9675\u57ce\u533a}})\n\n;Cities\nCities ({{lang|zh-hans|\u53bf\u7ea7\u5e02}} ''xianji shi'') administered by Dezhou are:\n*[[Leling]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e50\u9675\u5e02}})\n*[[Yucheng, Shandong|Yucheng]] ({{lang|zh|\u79b9\u57ce\u5e02}})\n\n;Counties\nCounties (\u53bf ''xian'') administered by Dezhou are:\n*[[Pingyuan County, Dezhou|Pingyuan]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5e73\u539f\u53bf}})\n*[[Xiajin County|Xiajin]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u590f\u6d25\u53bf}})\n*[[Wucheng County|Wucheng]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6b66\u57ce\u53bf}})\n*[[Qihe County|Qihe]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9f50\u6cb3\u53bf}})\n*[[Linyi County, Dezhou|Linyi]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e34\u9091\u53bf}})\n*[[Ningjin County, Shandong|Ningjin]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b81\u6d25\u53bf}})\n*[[Qingyun County|Qingyun]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5e86\u4e91\u53bf}})\n\n;Development zones\n*[[Dezhou Economic Development District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fb7\u5dde\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5f00\u53d1\u533a}})\n*[[Dezhou Yunhe Economic Development District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fb7\u5dde\u8fd0\u6cb3\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5f00\u53d1\u533a}})\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Map\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Dezhou.png|width=594|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=630|y=830|scale=594/2120|text=[[Decheng District|'''Decheng''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=980|y=880|scale=594/2120|text=[[Lingcheng District|'''Lingcheng''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1130|y=460|scale=594/2120|text=[[Ningjin County, Shandong|'''Ningjin<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1830|y=320|scale=594/2120|text=[[Qingyun County|'''Qingyun<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1260|y=1040|scale=594/2120|text=[[Linyi County, Dezhou|'''Linyi<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=970|y=1840|scale=594/2120|text=[[Qihe County|'''Qihe<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=680|y=1240|scale=594/2120|text=[[Pingyuan County, Dezhou|'''Pingyuan<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=220|y=1430|scale=594/2120|text=[[Xiajin County|'''Xiajin<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=300|y=1090|scale=594/2120|text=[[Wucheng County|'''Wucheng<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1510|y=510|scale=594/2120|text=[[Leling|'''Leling<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=880|y=1510|scale=594/2120|text=[[Yucheng, Shandong|'''Yucheng<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n</div>\n|}\n\n==Transport==\n\n=== Historical ===\nThe Yellow river and the Grand Canal runs through Dezhou, making it an important hub for cargo transit since antient times. It was described as \"Junction of Nine Arteries\" ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u4e5d\u8fbe\u5929\u8862}}) and \"Portal of the Capital\" ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u795e\u4eac\u95e8\u6237}}).\n\n=== Modern Era ===\nDezhou is connected via the Shijiazhuang-Dezhou railway, [[Shijiazhuang\u2013Jinan passenger railway|Shijiazhuang-Ji'nan HSR]], [[Beijing\u2013Shanghai railway|Beijing-Shanghai railway]], [[Beijing\u2013Shanghai high-speed railway|Beijing-Shanghai HSR]]. A small, single-track railway connects Dezhou with [[Dongying]] city as well.\n\nThe main expressway passing Dezhou is the [[G3 Beijing\u2013Taipei Expressway|G3 Beijing-Taipei Expressway]], running north\u2013south from it; other provincial expressways, as well as National Highway 104 and 105 offer connections in other directions for Dezhou\n\n==Tourism==\n{{main|Tourism in the People's Republic of China}}\nDezhou's biggest historical attraction is the tomb of [[Sultan Paduka Pahala]] of [[Sulu Province|Sulu]] (Philippines), who died in Dezhou on his return journey from a visit to the [[Yongle Emperor]] in 1417.<ref name=\":0\" /> The tomb is well preserved and has been declared a national heritage site. Descendants of the sultan's [[Muslim]] followers still live in Dezhou today, and are classified as the [[Hui people|Hui]] minority.\n\nOne of Dezhou's county Lingxian used to be a big county in China in history, when it was called Pingyuan County. Now part of the ancient city wall of Tang Dynasty still exists in the south of the region. Before the [[Three Kingdoms]] formed, one of the three emperors [[Liu Bei]] used to be the chief of the county, together with his fellows Guan Yu and Zhang Fei. In addition, it is the hometown of [[Dongfang Shuo]], the most well-known adviser during the reign of [[Emperor Wu of Han]] ; In Tang Dynasty, a major figure of Chinese calligraphy, [[Yan Zhenqing]], once took office as the administrator of the county. Today, a memorial hall for the two historic figures is built in the People's Park of Lingxian, where a lot of materials of Dongfang Shuo and stone inscriptions of Yan Zhenqing are preserved.\n\nFor tourist attractions, there is also a famous temple in Qingyun County. It's called Haidao Jinshan Temple, which is one of the biggest centers of [[Buddhism]] in Northern China. The most attractive scene is the underground aisle where the portrait of the hell is presented using high technology.\n\n==Industry==\nA new industrial zone hailed as the \"Solar Valley\" is being built for experimenting with clean- energy urban projects and massive use of household utilities such as solar-powered water-heaters. The Washington Post describes Dezhou's Solar Valley as the \"clean-tech version of Silicon Valley\".<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/16/AR2010051603482.html?sid=ST2010051701091 \"With Solar Valley project, China embarks on bold green technology mission\" by Andrew Higgins; Washington Post, May 17, 2010]</ref>\n\nNowadays one of the biggest and most famous industries in Dezhou is solar energy industry, with two main corporations included\u2014Himin Group ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u7687\u660e\u96c6\u56e2}}) and its partner Ecco Solar Group ({{zh|labels=no|s=\u4ebf\u5bb6\u80fd\u96c6\u56e2}}). Dezhou increased its international reputation when it was selected to follow previous hosts,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.isci-cities.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=58&Itemid=53 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726191258/http://www.isci-cities.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=58&Itemid=53 |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Daegu, South Korea (2004), [[Oxford]], UK (2006) and [[Adelaide]], [[Australia]] (2008) as host of the 2010 International Solar City Congress.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2009-02/09/content_7456117.htm Himin sees more shine in Dezhou's Solar Valley] [[China Daily]]</ref> Himin Group has developed into the world's largest solar water heater manufacturer and is also discovering new areas such as [[photoelectricity]].\n\n[[Greenpeace China]] cited Dezhou in May 2009 as an example of how [[renewable energy]] can become a more common reality throughout the world.<ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/china/en/campaigns/countdown-to-copenhagen/dezhou-solar-story On the sunny side of the street]</ref>\n\nDezhou also houses the world's largest solar-powered office building, covering around 75,000 square meters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecofriend.com/entry/eco-architecture-world-s-largest-solar-powered-office-building-unveiled-in-china/ |title=World's Largest Solar-powered Office building |access-date=2011-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824205443/http://www.ecofriend.com/entry/eco-architecture-world-s-largest-solar-powered-office-building-unveiled-in-china |archive-date=2011-08-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.alternative-energy-news.info/china-largest-solar-office-building/ \" \"]</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\"[[Dezhou College]]\"is a comprehensive college which was approved by the National Education Committee in March 2000. It is the aggregation of Dezhou Teachers\u2019 College, Dezhou Education College and Evening College Municipality, which has a 30-year history.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Dongfang Shuo]] (154 to 93 BC, The Western Han Dynasty), Writer and poet\n* [[Yan Zhenqing]] (709 to 784, The Tang Dynasty),  Calligrapher, poet\n* [[Ma Dehua]] (1945), actor, best known for his role as Zhu Bajie in the television series [[Journey to the West (1986 TV series)|Journey to the West]]\n* [[Han Hong (singer)|Han Hong]] (1971), Singer, songwriter, music producer, director\n* [[Zhang Yuqi]] (1986), Chinese actress\n*[[Ma Tianyu]] (1986), Chinese actor\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n*Dezhou is well known for its [[Braised Chicken|braised chicken]] and [[watermelon]].\n*The name of Dezhou is the same as the abbreviation of the Chinese name for the [[U.S. state]] of [[Texas]].\n*Pingyuan, Dezhou is the foundation place of [[Yihetuan]] ([[Boxer Rebellion]]) against the Eight Power Allied Force during the 1900s.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090228210558/http://www.dzcnc.com/ \u5fb7\u5dde\u9c81\u5317\u70ed\u7ebf]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071127014019/http://www.lingxian.ccoo.cn/travel/ \u9675\u53bf\u65c5\u6e38]\n*[http://www.dzwww.com/english/cities/200304291098.htm Dezhou]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090523074435/http://www.himin.com/english/index.html Himin Group]\n*[http://211.64.32.1/ Dezhou University]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180804141036/http://dz.gov.cn/ Government website of Dezhou] (in Simplified Chinese)\n\n{{Shandong topics}}\n{{Shandong}}\n{{Major cities along the Yellow River}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Shandong]]\n[[Category:Prefecture-level divisions of Shandong]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the modern city|the historical prefecture|De Prefecture}}\n{{About|city in China|State in the United States of America (whose Chinese translation is written the same way)|Texas