epublic of China]]. It borders the provincial capital of [[Jinan]] to the southeast, [[Liaocheng]] to the southwest, [[Binzhou]] to the northeast, and the province of [[Hebei]] to the north.\n\n==History==\n===Sulu Royal Family===\nThe King of [[Sulu]] [[Paduka Pahala]] from the [[List of sultans of Sulu#Pre-Sultanate Kings|first royal family on Sulu]] before the [[List of sultans of Sulu#Past Hashemite Sultans|Hashemites]] went on a tribute mission to the Ming dynasty [[Yongle Emperor]]. He died of natural causes in China and his two sons and wife were left in the care of [[Hui people|Hui Muslims]] in Dezhou, Shandong.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Steinhardt|first=Nancy Shatzman|title=China's Early Mosques|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|year=2015|isbn=978-1-4744-3721-9|location=Edinburgh|pages=161-162}}</ref> The two families descended from the two sons were given the surnames An and Wen by the Ming Emperors. They lived through the Ming and Qing dynasties and still live in Dezhou today.{{by whom|date=October 2015}}{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nThe Kingdom of Sulu was converted to Islam, and the Hashemite [[Sharif ul-H\u0101shim of Sulu]] arrived in Sulu and married a princess of the previous non-Hashemite royal family, founding the [[Sulu Sultanate]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nTausug delegations from Sulu have visited Dezhou to see the descendants of the previous royal family.{{Citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n==Administration==\n{{see also|Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China}}\nThe [[prefecture-level city|municipality]] of Dezhou comprises thirteen [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|county-level sub divisions]]:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dezhou.gov.cn/zjdz/xsqjj/ |title=Political divisions of Dezhou City |access-date=2011-06-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723132710/http://www.dezhou.gov.cn/zjdz/xsqjj/ |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n;Districts\n*[[Decheng District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fb7\u57ce\u533a}}). The government of the prefecture-level city is located in this sub division.\n*[[Lingcheng District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9675\u57ce\u533a}})\n\n;Cities\nCities ({{lang|zh-hans|\u53bf\u7ea7\u5e02}} ''xianji shi'') administered by Dezhou are:\n*[[Leling]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e50\u9675\u5e02}})\n*[[Yucheng, Shandong|Yucheng]] ({{lang|zh|\u79b9\u57ce\u5e02}})\n\n;Counties\nCounties (\u53bf ''xian'') administered by Dezhou are:\n*[[Pingyuan County, Dezhou|Pingyuan]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5e73\u539f\u53bf}})\n*[[Xiajin County|Xiajin]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u590f\u6d25\u53bf}})\n*[[Wucheng County|Wucheng]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6b66\u57ce\u53bf}})\n*[[Qihe County|Qihe]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u9f50\u6cb3\u53bf}})\n*[[Linyi County, Dezhou|Linyi]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e34\u9091\u53bf}})\n*[[Ningjin County, Shandong|Ningjin]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b81\u6d25\u53bf}})\n*[[Qingyun County|Qingyun]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5e86\u4e91\u53bf}})\n\n;Development zones\n*[[Dezhou Economic Development District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fb7\u5dde\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5f00\u53d1\u533a}})\n*[[Dezhou Yunhe Economic Development District]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5fb7\u5dde\u8fd0\u6cb3\u7ecf\u6d4e\u5f00\u53d1\u533a}})\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Map\n|-\n| align=\"center\"| <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative Division Dezhou.png|width=594|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=630|y=830|scale=594/2120|text=[[Decheng District|'''Decheng''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=980|y=880|scale=594/2120|text=[[Lingcheng District|'''Lingcheng''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1130|y=460|scale=594/2120|text=[[Ningjin County, Shandong|'''Ningjin<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1830|y=320|scale=594/2120|text=[[Qingyun County|'''Qingyun<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1260|y=1040|scale=594/2120|text=[[Linyi County, Dezhou|'''Linyi<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=970|y=1840|scale=594/2120|text=[[Qihe County|'''Qihe<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=680|y=1240|scale=594/2120|text=[[Pingyuan County, Dezhou|'''Pingyuan<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=220|y=1430|scale=594/2120|text=[[Xiajin County|'''Xiajin<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=300|y=1090|scale=594/2120|text=[[Wucheng County|'''Wucheng<br>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1510|y=510|scale=594/2120|text=[[Leling|'''Leling<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=880|y=1510|scale=594/2120|text=[[Yucheng, Shandong|'''Yucheng<br>{{small|(city)}}''']]}}\n</div>\n|}\n\n==Transport==\n\n=== Historical ===\nThe Yellow river and the Grand Canal runs through Dezhou, making it an important hub for cargo transit since antient times. It was described as \"Junction of Nine Arteries\" (\u4e5d\u8fbe\u5929\u8862) and \"Portal of the Capital\" (\u795e\u4eac\u95e8\u6237).\n\n=== Modern Era ===\nDezhou is connected via the Shijiazhuang-Dezhou railway, [[Shijiazhuang\u2013Jinan passenger railway|Shijiazhuang-Ji'nan HSR]], [[Beijing\u2013Shanghai railway|Beijing-Shanghai railway]], [[Beijing\u2013Shanghai high-speed railway|Beijing-Shanghai HSR]]. A small, single-track railway connects Dezhou with [[Dongying]] city as well.\n\nThe main expressway passing Dezhou is the [[G3 Beijing\u2013Taipei Expressway|G3 Beijing-Taipei Expressway]], running north\u2013south from it; other provincial expressways, as well as National Highway 104 and 105 offer connections in other directions for Dezhou\n\n==Tourism==\n{{main|Tourism in the People's Republic of China}}\nDezhou's biggest historical attraction is the tomb of [[Sultan Paduka Pahala]] of [[Sulu Province|Sulu]] (Philippines), who died in Dezhou on his return journey from a visit to the [[Yongle Emperor]] in 1417.<ref name=\":0\" /> The tomb is well preserved and has been declared a national heritage site. Descendants of the sultan's [[Muslim]] followers still live in Dezhou today, and are classified as the [[Hui people|Hui]] minority.\n\nOne of Dezhou's county Lingxian used to be a big county in China in history, when it was called Pingyuan County. Now part of the ancient city wall of Tang Dynasty still exists in the south of the region. Before the [[Three Kingdoms]] formed, one of the three emperors [[Liu Bei]] used to be the chief of the county, together with his fellows Guan Yu and Zhang Fei. In addition, it is the hometown of [[Dongfang Shuo]] (\u4e1c\u65b9\u6714), the most well-known adviser during the reign of [[Emperor Wu of Han]] ; In Tang Dynasty, a major figure of Chinese calligraphy, [[Yan Zhenqing]], once took office as the administrator of the county. Today, a memorial hall for the two historic figures is built in the People's Park of Lingxian, where a lot of materials of Dongfang Shuo and stone inscriptions of Yan Zhenqing are preserved.\n\nFor tourist attractions, there is also a famous temple in Qingyun County. It's called Haidao Jinshan Temple, which is one of the biggest centers of [[Buddhism]] in Northern China. The most attractive scene is the underground aisle where the portrait of the hell is presented using high technology.\n\n==Industry==\nA new industrial zone hailed as the \"Solar Valley\" is being built for experimenting with clean- energy urban projects and massive use of household utilities such as solar-powered water-heaters. The Washington Post describes Dezhou's Solar Valley as the \"clean-tech version of Silicon Valley\".<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/16/AR2010051603482.html?sid=ST2010051701091 \"With Solar Valley project, China embarks on bold green technology mission\" by Andrew Higgins; Washington Post, May 17, 2010]</ref>\n\nNowadays one of the biggest and most famous industries in Dezhou is solar energy industry, with two main corporations included\u2014Himin Group (\u7687\u660e\u96c6\u56e2) and its partner Ecco Solar Group (\u4ebf\u5bb6\u80fd\u96c6\u56e2). Dezhou increased its international reputation when it was selected to follow previous hosts,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.isci-cities.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=58&Itemid=53 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726191258/http://www.isci-cities.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=58&Itemid=53 |archive-date=2011-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Daegu, South Korea (2004), [[Oxford]], UK (2006) and [[Adelaide]], [[Australia]] (2008) as host of the 2010 International Solar City Congress.<ref>[http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2009-02/09/content_7456117.htm Himin sees more shine in Dezhou's Solar Valley] [[China Daily]]</ref> Himin Group has developed into the world's largest solar water heater manufacturer and is also discovering new areas such as [[photoelectricity]].\n\n[[Greenpeace China]] cited Dezhou in May 2009 as an example of how [[renewable energy]] can become a more common reality throughout the world.<ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/china/en/campaigns/countdown-to-copenhagen/dezhou-solar-story On the sunny side of the street]</ref>\n\nDezhou also houses the world's largest solar-powered office building, covering around 75,000 square meters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ecofriend.com/entry/eco-architecture-world-s-largest-solar-powered-office-building-unveiled-in-china/ |title=World's Largest Solar-powered Office building |access-date=2011-10-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824205443/http://www.ecofriend.com/entry/eco-architecture-world-s-largest-solar-powered-office-building-unveiled-in-china |archive-date=2011-08-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.alternative-energy-news.info/china-largest-solar-office-building/ \" \"]</ref>\n\n==Education==\n\"[[Dezhou College]]\"is a comprehensive college which was approved by the National Education Committee in March 2000. It is the aggregation of Dezhou Teachers\u2019 College, Dezhou Education College and Evening College Municipality, which has a 30-year history.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Dongfang Shuo]] (154 to 93 BC, The Western Han Dynasty), Writer and poet\n* [[Yan Zhenqing]] (709 to 784, The Tang Dynasty),  Calligrapher, poet\n* [[Ma Dehua]] (1945), actor, best known for his role as Zhu Bajie in the television series [[Journey to the West (1986 TV series)|Journey to the West]]\n* [[Han Hong (singer)|Han Hong]] (1971), Singer, songwriter, music producer, director\n* [[Zhang Yuqi]] (1986), Chinese actress\n*[[Ma Tianyu]] (1986), Chinese actor\n\n==Miscellaneous==\n*Dezhou is well known for its [[Braised Chicken|braised chicken]] and [[watermelon]].\n*The name of Dezhou is the same as the abbreviation of the Chinese name for the [[U.S. state]] of [[Texas]].\n*Pingyuan, Dezhou is the foundation place of [[Yihetuan]] ([[Boxer Rebellion]]) against the Eight Power Allied Force during the 1900s.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090228210558/http://www.dzcnc.com/ \u5fb7\u5dde\u9c81\u5317\u70ed\u7ebf]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071127014019/http://www.lingxian.ccoo.cn/travel/ \u9675\u53bf\u65c5\u6e38]\n*[http://www.dzwww.com/english/cities/200304291098.htm Dezhou]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090523074435/http://www.himin.com/english/index.html Himin Group]\n*[http://211.64.32.1/ Dezhou University]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180804141036/http://dz.gov.cn/ Government website of Dezhou] (in Simplified Chinese)\n\n{{Shandong topics}}\n{{Shandong}}\n{{Major cities along the Yellow River}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Shandong]]\n[[Category:Prefecture-level divisions of Shandong]]\n", "name_user": "CaradhrasAiguo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Ref work: script-title, quote, zh in Publisher, etc", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dezhou"}
{"title_page": "Panic buying", "text_new": "{{short description|Act of buying unusually large amounts of a product in anticipation of a shortage of supply or rapid increase in cost}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020|cs1-dates=y}}\n{{multiple image|perrow=1|total_width=250\n|align=right\n|image1=Shelves usually selling toilet paper and tissues are empty, due to Coronavirus panic buying 2.jpg\n|caption1=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|image2=Empty toilet-paper shelves at Ica Focus - Gbg.jpg\n|caption2=[[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]]\n|footer=Aftermath of selective panic buying of [[toilet paper]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n}}\n\n'''Panic buying''' (alternatively rendered as '''panic-buying''') occurs when [[consumer]]s buy unusually large amounts of a product in anticipation of, or after, a [[disaster]] or perceived disaster, or in anticipation of a large price increase or [[shortage]]. \n\nPanic buying is a type of [[herd behavior]].<ref>Bruce Jones & David Steven, ''The New Politics of Strategic Resources: Energy and Food Security Challenges in the 21st Century'' (eds. David Steven, Emily O'Brien & Bruce D. Jone: Brookings Institution Press, 2015), p. 12.</ref> It is of interest in [[consumer behavior]] theory, the broad field of economic study dealing with explanations for \"[[collective action]] such as [[fad]]s and fashions, [[stock market]] movements, runs on [[nondurable goods]], buying sprees, [[hoarding]], and [[banking panic]]s.\"<ref>William M. Strahle & E. H. Bonfield. [https://www.acrwebsite.org/volumes/6964/volumes/v16/NA-16 Understanding Consumer Panic: a Sociological Perspective], ''Advances in Consumer Research'', Volume 16, 1989, eds. Thomas K. Srull, Provo, UT: Association for Consumer Research, pp. 567-573.</ref>\n\nPanic-buying can lead to genuine shortages regardless of whether the risk of a shortage is real or perceived; the latter scenario is an example of [[self-fulfilling prophecy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Toxic leak threat to Chinese city| url=https://www.cantonrep.com/news/20200303/we-need-to-calm-down-coronavirus-fears-spark-lsquopanic-buyingrsquo-of-toilet-paper-hand-sanitizer-and-water|work=The Repository|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPanic-buying began to receive widespread attention in early 2020 during the escalation of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]], when many stores around the world were depleted of items such as toilet paper, foodstuff, hygiene products and other goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideretail.com.au/news/supermarkets-report-panic-buying-over-coronavirus-fears-202003|title=Supermarkets report panic buying over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-03|website=Inside Retail|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n==Examples==\nPanic buying occurred before, during, or following these incidents:\n* [[1922&ndash;1923 German hyperinflation]]\n* [[1943 Bengal famine]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Archibald Percival Wavell|authorlink1=Archibald Wavell, 1st Earl Wavell|editor1-last=Moon|editor1-first=Penderel|title=Wavell: The Viceroy's Journal|url=https://archive.org/details/wavellviceroysjo0000wave|url-access=registration|date=1973|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/wavellviceroysjo0000wave/page/34 34]}}</ref>\n* 1962 [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] \u2013 led to panic buying of canned foods in the United States<ref>{{cite book|author1=Alice L. George|title=Awaiting Armageddon: How Americans Faced the Cuban Missile Crisis|date=2003|publisher=The University of North Carolina Press|isbn=0807828289|page=[https://archive.org/details/awaitingarmagedd0000geor/page/78 78]|url=https://archive.org/details/awaitingarmagedd0000geor|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n* The [[1979&ndash;1980 oil crisis]] led to panic buying of oil, led by Japan.<ref>Mamdouch G. Salameh, \"Oil Crises, Historical Perspective\" in ''Concise Encyclopedia of the History of Energy'' (ed. Cutler J. Cleveland: Elsevier, 2009), p. 196.</ref>\n* [[Year 2000 problem]] \u2013 food<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lohr|first1=Steve|title=Technology and 2000 \u2013 Momentous Relief; Computers Prevail in First Hours of '00|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/01/01/us/1-1-00-technology-2000-momentous-relief-computers-prevail-first-hours-00.html?pagewanted=all|work=New York Times|date=1 January 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Millenium Bug threatens food supply systems \u2013 developing countries are also vulnerable, FAO warns|url=http://www.fao.org/News/1999/990302-e.htm|publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]|date=19 April 1999}}</ref>\n* 2001 - panic buying of metals, gold and oil on international [[commodity markets]] following the [[September 11 attacks]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2001/09/11/markets/oil/|title=Oil and gold prices spike|date=11 September 2001|website=money.cnn.com}}</ref>\n* In January and February 2003, during the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]], several rounds of panic buying of various products (including salt, rice, vinegar, [[vegetable oil]], [[antibiotic]]s, masks, and [[traditional Chinese medicine]]) took place in the Chinese province of [[Guangdong]] and in neighboring areas such as [[Hainan]] and [[Hong Kong]].<ref>Huiling Ding, ''Rhetoric of a Global Epidemic: Transcultural Communication about SARS'' (Southern Illinois University Press, 2014), pp. 70, 72, 83, 103, 111.</ref>\n* 2000 and 2005 [[UK fuel protests]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Collins|first1=Nick|title=EU ban on traditional lightbulbs prompts panic buying|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/6082853/EU-ban-on-traditional-lightbulbs-prompts-panic-buying.html|work=The Telegraph|date=25 August 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc20000914\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/924329.stm |title=UK fuel blockades tumble |date=14 September 2000 |publisher= BBC News|accessdate=12 January 2008}}</ref>\n* [[2005 Jilin chemical plant explosions]] \u2013 water, food<ref>{{cite news | title= Toxic leak threat to Chinese city| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4462760.stm | publisher= BBC News| date = 23 November 2005}}</ref>\n* [[2008\u20132013 United States ammunition shortage]] \u2013 Panic buying by gun owners who feared tougher [[gun control]] laws under President [[Barack Obama]] was one cause of ammunition shortages.<ref>Danielle Kurtzleben, [https://www.vox.com/2014/7/1/5845524/the-ammunition-shortage-is-a-real-thing-heres-why-it-happened Here's why the ammunition shortage went on for years], ''Vox'' (1 July 2014).</ref><ref>Stephanie Clifford, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/22/nyregion/gun-shop-owners-report-spike-in-sales-as-enthusiasts-fear-possible-new-laws.html Shop Owners Report Rise in Firearm Sales as Buyers Fear Possible New Laws], ''New York Times'' (22 December 2012).</ref>\n* In September 2013 during the [[Economic policy of the Nicol\u00e1s Maduro administration|Venezuelan economic crisis]], the Venezuelan government temporarily took over the Aragua-based Paper Manufacturing Company [[toilet paper]] plant to manage the \"production, marketing and distribution\" of toilet paper following months of depleted stocks of basic goods\u2014including toilet paper\u2014and foodstuffs, such as rice and cooking oil. Blame for the shortages was placed on \"ill-conceived government policies such as price controls on basic goods and tight restrictions on foreign currency\" and hoarding.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Facing shortages, Venezuela takes over toilet paper factory |work=CNN |first1=Marilia |last1=Brochetto |first2=Greg |last2=Botelho| access-date = 13 March 2020 |date=12 September 2013| url = https://www.cnn.com/2013/09/21/world/americas/venezuela-toilet-paper/}}</ref>\n* ''[[Dakazo]]'' \u2013 Amid decreased support before the [[2013 Venezuelan municipal elections]], Venezuelan president [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] announced the military occupation of stores on 8 November 2013, proclaiming \"Leave nothing on the shelves!\"<ref name=\"ETnov2014\">{{cite news|last1=Lezama Aranguren|first1=Erick|url=http://eltiempo.com.ve/venezuela/situacion/la-resaca-del-dakazo-un-ano-despues/161509|title=La resaca del \"dakazo\", un a\u00f1o despu\u00e9s|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=12 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112122704/http://eltiempo.com.ve/venezuela/situacion/la-resaca-del-dakazo-un-ano-despues/161509|archive-date=12 November 2014|agency=[[El Tiempo (Anzo\u00e1tegui)|El Tiempo]]}}</ref> The announcement of lowered prices sparked looting in multiple cities across Venezuela.<ref name=\"EUROnov2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2013/11/12/watch-looting-in-venezuela-after-government-launches-attack-on-bourgeois-paras/|title=Watch: Looting in Venezuela after government launches attack on \u2018bourgeois parasites\u2019|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=12 November 2014|agency=EuroNews}}</ref> By the end of the Dakazo, many Venezuelan stores were left empty of their goods.<ref name=\"ETnov2014\"/> A year later in November 2014, some stores still remained empty following the Dakazo.<ref name=\"ETnov2014\"/>\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] \u2013 Panic-buying became a major international phenomenon in February and March 2020, when grocery stores around the world were depleted of items such as masks, food, bottled water, toilet paper (limited),<ref>[https://marker.medium.com/what-everyones-getting-wrong-about-the-toilet-paper-shortage-c812e1358fe0 What everyone's getting wrong about the toilet paper shortage] Medium</ref> hand sanitizer, and rubbing alcohol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-24/virus-outbreak-drives-italians-to-panic-buying-of-masks-and-food|title=Virus Outbreak Drives Italians to Panic-Buying of Masks and Food|last=Sirletti|first=Sonia|last2=Remondini|first2=Chiara|date=24 February 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 February 2020|last3=Lepido|first3=Daniele}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title = The economics of the toilet paper panic\u2014and why more stockpiling is inevitable|work=Macleans|accessdate = 13 March 2020| url = https://www.macleans.ca/economy/economicanalysis/the-toilet-paper-panic-and-why-more-stockpiling-is-inevitable/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title = Virus panic buying prompts toilet paper rationing in Australia| work = CTVNews| accessdate = 13 March 2020| date = 4 March 2020| url = https://www.ctvnews.ca/world/virus-panic-buying-prompts-toilet-paper-rationing-in-australia-1.4837956}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/coles-limits-toilet-paper-purchases-to-one-pack-per-person-20200308-p547xb.html |title=Coles and Woolworths further limit toilet paper purchases as supply sells out in an hour |agency=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[smh.com.au]] |date=8 March 2020 |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title = 'It's crazy': Panic buying forces stores to limit purchases of toilet paper and masks|publisher=CNN| accessdate = 13 March 2020| url = https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/business/coronavirus-global-panic-buying-toilet-paper/index.html}}</ref> \n<gallery>\nFile:Mexico City Empty Shelves in a Supermarket Swine Flu.jpg|Shoppers in [[Mexico City]] panic buying canned food during the [[2009 flu pandemic]]\nFile:Dakazo.png|Venezuelans grabbing for items during the ''[[Dakazo]]'', an event of the [[crisis in Venezuela]]\nFile:DSC05532 (49675496857).jpg|Shoppers in [[London]] panic buying canned food and toilet paper during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\nFile:Covid19amazon.jpg|As a result of panic buying during the COVID-19 pandemic, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] restricted sales of [[hand sanitizer]] to medical professionals and government agencies in March 2020.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Panic selling]]\n* [[Rationing]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{cc}}\n[[Category:Consumer behaviour]]\n[[Category:Scarcity]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Act of buying unusually large amounts of a product in anticipation of a shortage of supply or rapid increase in cost}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020|cs1-dates=y}}\n{{multiple image|perrow=1|total_width=250\n|align=right\n|image1=Shelves usually selling toilet paper and tissues are empty, due to Coronavirus panic buying 2.jpg\n|caption1=[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|image2=Empty toilet-paper shelves at Ica Focus - Gbg.jpg\n|caption2=[[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]]\n|footer=Aftermath of selective panic buying of [[toilet paper]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].\n}}\n\n'''Panic buying''' (alternatively rendered as '''panic-buying''') occurs when [[consumer]]s buy unusually large amounts of a product in anticipation of, or after, a [[disaster]] or perceived disaster, or in anticipation of a large price increase or [[shortage]]. \n\nPanic buying is a type of [[herd behavior]].<ref>Bruce Jones & David Steven, ''The New Politics of Strategic Resources: Energy and Food Security Challenges in the 21st Century'' (eds. David Steven, Emily O'Brien & Bruce D. Jone: Brookings Institution Press, 2015), p. 12.</ref> It is of interest in [[consumer behavior]] theory, the broad field of economic study dealing with explanations for \"[[collective action]] such as [[fad]]s and fashions, [[stock market]] movements, runs on [[nondurable goods]], buying sprees, [[hoarding]], and [[banking panic]]s.\"<ref>William M. Strahle & E. H. Bonfield. [https://www.acrwebsite.org/volumes/6964/volumes/v16/NA-16 Understanding Consumer Panic: a Sociological Perspective], ''Advances in Consumer Research'', Volume 16, 1989, eds. Thomas K. Srull, Provo, UT: Association for Consumer Research, pp. 567-573.</ref>\n\nPanic-buying can lead to genuine shortages regardless of whether the risk of a shortage is real or perceived; the latter scenario is an example of [[self-fulfilling prophecy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Toxic leak threat to Chinese city| url=https://www.cantonrep.com/news/20200303/we-need-to-calm-down-coronavirus-fears-spark-lsquopanic-buyingrsquo-of-toilet-paper-hand-sanitizer-and-water|work=The Repository|date=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nPanic-buying began to receive widespread attention in early 2020 during the escalation of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]], when many stores around the world were depleted of items such as toilet paper, foodstuff, hygiene products and other goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideretail.com.au/news/supermarkets-report-panic-buying-over-coronavirus-fears-202003|title=Supermarkets report panic buying over coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-03|website=Inside Retail|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> \n\n==Examples==\nPanic buying occurred before, during, or following these incidents:\n* [[1922&ndash;1923 German hyperinflation]]\n* [[1943 Bengal famine]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Archibald Percival Wavell|authorlink1=Archibald Wavell, 1st Earl Wavell|editor1-last=Moon|editor1-first=Penderel|title=Wavell: The Viceroy's Journal|url=https://archive.org/details/wavellviceroysjo0000wave|url-access=registration|date=1973|publisher=Oxford University Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/wavellviceroysjo0000wave/page/34 34]}}</ref>\n* 1962 [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] \u2013 led to panic buying of canned foods in the United States<ref>{{cite book|author1=Alice L. George|title=Awaiting Armageddon: How Americans Faced the Cuban Missile Crisis|date=2003|publisher=The University of North Carolina Press|isbn=0807828289|page=[https://archive.org/details/awaitingarmagedd0000geor/page/78 78]|url=https://archive.org/details/awaitingarmagedd0000geor|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n* The [[1979&ndash;1980 oil crisis]] led to panic buying of oil, led by Japan.<ref>Mamdouch G. Salameh, \"Oil Crises, Historical Perspective\" in ''Concise Encyclopedia of the History of Energy'' (ed. Cutler J. Cleveland: Elsevier, 2009), p. 196.</ref>\n* [[Year 2000 problem]] \u2013 food<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lohr|first1=Steve|title=Technology and 2000 \u2013 Momentous Relief; Computers Prevail in First Hours of '00|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/01/01/us/1-1-00-technology-2000-momentous-relief-computers-prevail-first-hours-00.html?pagewanted=all|work=New York Times|date=1 January 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The Millenium Bug threatens food supply systems \u2013 developing countries are also vulnerable, FAO warns|url=http://www.fao.org/News/1999/990302-e.htm|publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]|date=19 April 1999}}</ref>\n* 2001 - panic buying of metals, gold and oil on international [[commodity markets]] following the [[September 11 attacks]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2001/09/11/markets/oil/|title=Oil and gold prices spike|date=11 September 2001|website=money.cnn.com}}</ref>\n* In January and February 2003, during the [[2002\u20132004 SARS outbreak|SARS outbreak]], several rounds of panic buying of various products (including salt, rice, vinegar, [[vegetable oil]], [[antibiotic]]s, masks, and [[traditional Chinese medicine]]) took place in the Chinese province of [[Guangdong]] and in neighboring areas such as [[Hainan]] and [[Hong Kong]].<ref>Huiling Ding, ''Rhetoric of a Global Epidemic: Transcultural Communication about SARS'' (Southern Illinois University Press, 2014), pp. 70, 72, 83, 103, 111.</ref>\n* 2000 and 2005 [[UK fuel protests]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Collins|first1=Nick|title=EU ban on traditional lightbulbs prompts panic buying|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/6082853/EU-ban-on-traditional-lightbulbs-prompts-panic-buying.html|work=The Telegraph|date=25 August 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc20000914\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/924329.stm |title=UK fuel blockades tumble |date=14 September 2000 |publisher= BBC News|accessdate=12 January 2008}}</ref>\n* [[2005 Jilin chemical plant explosions]] \u2013 water, food<ref>{{cite news | title= Toxic leak threat to Chinese city| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/4462760.stm | publisher= BBC News| date = 23 November 2005}}</ref>\n* [[2008\u20132013 United States ammunition shortage]] \u2013 Panic buying by gun owners who feared tougher [[gun control]] laws under President [[Barack Obama]] was one cause of ammunition shortages.<ref>Danielle Kurtzleben, [https://www.vox.com/2014/7/1/5845524/the-ammunition-shortage-is-a-real-thing-heres-why-it-happened Here's why the ammunition shortage went on for years], ''Vox'' (1 July 2014).</ref><ref>Stephanie Clifford, [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/22/nyregion/gun-shop-owners-report-spike-in-sales-as-enthusiasts-fear-possible-new-laws.html Shop Owners Report Rise in Firearm Sales as Buyers Fear Possible New Laws], ''New York Times'' (22 December 2012).</ref>\n* In September 2013 during the [[Economic policy of the Nicol\u00e1s Maduro administration|Venezuelan economic crisis]], the Venezuelan government temporarily took over the Aragua-based Paper Manufacturing Company [[toilet paper]] plant to manage the \"production, marketing and distribution\" of toilet paper following months of depleted stocks of basic goods\u2014including toilet paper\u2014and foodstuffs, such as rice and cooking oil. Blame for the shortages was placed on \"ill-conceived government policies such as price controls on basic goods and tight restrictions on foreign currency\" and hoarding.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Facing shortages, Venezuela takes over toilet paper factory |work=CNN |first1=Marilia |last1=Brochetto |first2=Greg |last2=Botelho| access-date = 13 March 2020 |date=12 September 2013| url = https://www.cnn.com/2013/09/21/world/americas/venezuela-toilet-paper/}}</ref>\n* ''[[Dakazo]]'' \u2013 Amid decreased support before the [[2013 Venezuelan municipal elections]], Venezuelan president [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] announced the military occupation of stores on 8 November 2013, proclaiming \"Leave nothing on the shelves!\"<ref name=\"ETnov2014\">{{cite news|last1=Lezama Aranguren|first1=Erick|url=http://eltiempo.com.ve/venezuela/situacion/la-resaca-del-dakazo-un-ano-despues/161509|title=La resaca del \"dakazo\", un a\u00f1o despu\u00e9s|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=12 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112122704/http://eltiempo.com.ve/venezuela/situacion/la-resaca-del-dakazo-un-ano-despues/161509|archive-date=12 November 2014|agency=[[El Tiempo (Anzo\u00e1tegui)|El Tiempo]]}}</ref> The announcement of lowered prices sparked looting in multiple cities across Venezuela.<ref name=\"EUROnov2013\">{{cite news|url=http://www.euronews.com/2013/11/12/watch-looting-in-venezuela-after-government-launches-attack-on-bourgeois-paras/|title=Watch: Looting in Venezuela after government launches attack on \u2018bourgeois parasites\u2019|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=12 November 2014|agency=EuroNews}}</ref> By the end of the Dakazo, many Venezuelan stores were left empty of their goods.<ref name=\"ETnov2014\"/> A year later in November 2014, some stores still remained empty following the Dakazo.<ref name=\"ETnov2014\"/>\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] \u2013 Panic-buying became a major international phenomenon in February and March 2020, when grocery stores around the world were depleted of items such as masks, food, bottled water, toilet paper (limited)<ref>[https://marker.medium.com/what-everyones-getting-wrong-about-the-toilet-paper-shortage-c812e1358fe0 What everyone's getting wrong about the toilet paper shortage] Medium</ref>, hand sanitizer, and rubbing alcohol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-24/virus-outbreak-drives-italians-to-panic-buying-of-masks-and-food|title=Virus Outbreak Drives Italians to Panic-Buying of Masks and Food|last=Sirletti|first=Sonia|last2=Remondini|first2=Chiara|date=24 February 2020|website=Bloomberg|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=29 February 2020|last3=Lepido|first3=Daniele}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title = The economics of the toilet paper panic\u2014and why more stockpiling is inevitable|work=Macleans|accessdate = 13 March 2020| url = https://www.macleans.ca/economy/economicanalysis/the-toilet-paper-panic-and-why-more-stockpiling-is-inevitable/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title = Virus panic buying prompts toilet paper rationing in Australia| work = CTVNews| accessdate = 13 March 2020| date = 4 March 2020| url = https://www.ctvnews.ca/world/virus-panic-buying-prompts-toilet-paper-rationing-in-australia-1.4837956}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/companies/coles-limits-toilet-paper-purchases-to-one-pack-per-person-20200308-p547xb.html |title=Coles and Woolworths further limit toilet paper purchases as supply sells out in an hour |agency=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[smh.com.au]] |date=8 March 2020 |access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title = 'It's crazy': Panic buying forces stores to limit purchases of toilet paper and masks|publisher=CNN| accessdate = 13 March 2020| url = https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/business/coronavirus-global-panic-buying-toilet-paper/index.html}}</ref> \n<gallery>\nFile:Mexico City Empty Shelves in a Supermarket Swine Flu.jpg|Shoppers in [[Mexico City]] panic buying canned food during the [[2009 flu pandemic]]\nFile:Dakazo.png|Venezuelans grabbing for items during the ''[[Dakazo]]'', an event of the [[crisis in Venezuela]]\nFile:DSC05532 (49675496857).jpg|Shoppers in [[London]] panic buying canned food and toilet paper during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\nFile:Covid19amazon.jpg|As a result of panic buying during the COVID-19 pandemic, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] restricted sales of [[hand sanitizer]] to medical professionals and government agencies in March 2020.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Panic selling]]\n* [[Rationing]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{cc}}\n[[Category:Consumer behaviour]]\n[[Category:Scarcity]]\n", "name_user": "Useight", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExamples:fixed comma placement", "url_page":